      "role": "assistant",
      "contents": [
        {
          "$type": "text",
          "text": "{\"workouts\":[{\"day_of_week\":1,\"workout_type\":\"Easy\",\"title\":\"Easy Aerobic Run\",\"target_distance_km\":8,\"target_duration_minutes\":45,\"target_pace_easy_sec_per_km\":339,\"target_pace_fast_sec_per_km\":322,\"segments\":[{\"segment_type\":\"Warmup\",\"duration_minutes\":5,\"target_pace_sec_per_km\":356,\"intensity\":\"Easy\",\"repetitions\":1,\"notes\":\"Start very easy, let your body wake up. First 5 minutes are just about getting moving.\"},{\"segment_type\":\"Work\",\"duration_minutes\":35,\"target_pace_sec_per_km\":339,\"intensity\":\"Easy\",\"repetitions\":1,\"notes\":\"Settle into a comfortable, conversational pace. You should be able to speak in full sentences throughout. This is aerobic base work — resist the urge to push.\"},{\"segment_type\":\"Cooldown\",\"duration_minutes\":5,\"target_pace_sec_per_km\":356,\"intensity\":\"Easy\",\"repetitions\":1,\"notes\":\"Ease off the pace for the final 5 minutes. Finish feeling like you could have run further.\"}],\"warmup_notes\":\"No structured warmup needed beyond the easy first 5 minutes of the run itself. Dynamic leg swings and hip circles before you head out are a nice addition.\",\"cooldown_notes\":\"Walk 2–3 minutes after finishing. Light calf and hip flexor stretching, especially given your Achilles history on the left side.\",\"coaching_notes\":\"This Monday run sets the tone for the week — it's purely aerobic, low-stress work that supports your aerobic base without adding fatigue. At your VDOT of 46.7, easy running at 5:22–5:56/km is doing real physiological work: building mitochondrial density, improving fat oxidation, and reinforcing your running economy. The temptation is always to drift faster, but keeping this genuinely easy is what makes your harder days actually work. Think of this as an investment in Thursday.\",\"perceived_effort\":4},{\"day_of_week\":2,\"workout_type\":\"Interval\",\"title\":\"VO2Max Intervals\",\"target_distance_km\":10,\"target_duration_minutes\":50,\"target_pace_easy_sec_per_km\":339,\"target_pace_fast_sec_per_km\":251,\"segments\":[{\"segment_type\":\"Warmup\",\"duration_minutes\":12,\"target_pace_sec_per_km\":339,\"intensity\":\"Easy\",\"repetitions\":1,\"notes\":\"2 km easy jog to get the legs moving. Include 4–6 strides of 20 seconds at interval pace in the final 2 minutes of warmup to prime your neuromuscular system before the hard work begins.\"},{\"segment_type\":\"Work\",\"duration_minutes\":5,\"target_pace_sec_per_km\":251,\"intensity\":\"VO2Max\",\"repetitions\":5,\"notes\":\"5 x 1 km at 4:11/km (interval pace). This is hard but controlled — not a sprint. You should feel like you're working at about 95% effort. Each rep should feel similar; if the last two feel dramatically harder, you may have gone out too fast on the first.\"},{\"segment_type\":\"Recovery\",\"duration_minutes\":10,\"target_pace_sec_per_km\":356,\"intensity\":\"Easy\",\"repetitions\":5,\"notes\":\"400m jog recovery between each interval. Keep moving — don't stop and stand. The recovery jog should take roughly 2 minutes. Use it to reset your breathing before the next rep.\"},{\"segment_type\":\"Cooldown\",\"duration_minutes\":10,\"target_pace_sec_per_km\":339,\"intensity\":\"Easy\",\"repetitions\":1,\"notes\":\"1.5–2 km easy jog to flush the legs. This is not optional — it accelerates lactate clearance and helps you recover faster for the rest of the week.\"}],\"warmup_notes\":\"2 km easy jog followed by dynamic drills: leg swings, high knees, butt kicks, and 4–6 x 20-second strides building to interval pace. Give yourself a full 10–12 minutes before the first hard rep.\",\"cooldown_notes\":\"Minimum 1.5 km easy jog after the final interval. Follow with calf raises and eccentric heel drops (3 x 15 each side) as Achilles prehab — this is a good habit given your 2023 history.\",\"coaching_notes\":\"Interval work at 4:11/km targets your VO2max — the ceiling of your aerobic engine. For a maintenance phase, the goal isn't to push this ceiling higher, but to keep it where it is. Five 1 km reps is a proven, manageable dose that maintains the adaptation without creating excessive fatigue. Your recent training history shows you've been handling this session well (5 x 1 km on March 8 and 15), so this is a direct continuation of that pattern. The key is honest pacing on rep 1 — going out at 4:05 feels fine but costs you on rep 4 and 5.\",\"perceived_effort\":8},{\"day_of_week\":3,\"workout_type\":\"Recovery\",\"title\":\"Recovery Run\",\"target_distance_km\":6,\"target_duration_minutes\":36,\"target_pace_easy_sec_per_km\":356,\"target_pace_fast_sec_per_km\":356,\"segments\":[{\"segment_type\":\"Work\",\"duration_minutes\":36,\"target_pace_sec_per_km\":356,\"intensity\":\"Easy\",\"repetitions\":1,\"notes\":\"This run should feel almost embarrassingly easy after yesterday's intervals. Stay at the slow end of easy pace (5:56/km) or even slower if your legs are still heavy. There is no minimum pace here — slower is fine.\"}],\"warmup_notes\":\"Walk for 3–5 minutes before starting. Your legs will likely be fatigued from Tuesday's intervals — let them ease in gradually.\",\"cooldown_notes\":\"Walk 3–5 minutes after finishing. This is a great day for foam rolling the calves and Achilles area, and for any mobility work you enjoy.\",\"coaching_notes\":\"Wednesday is a deliberate recovery run — not a junk mile day, but an active recovery tool. Running at a very easy effort (5:56/km or slower) increases blood flow to fatigued muscles, accelerates waste product clearance, and keeps your aerobic system ticking without adding meaningful stress. The science here is clear: light movement the day after hard intervals outperforms complete rest for next-day readiness. Your training history shows you've been doing exactly this pattern, and it's working well. Protect this run's easy nature fiercely.\",\"perceived_effort\":3},{\"day_of_week\":4,\"workout_type\":\"Tempo\",\"title\":\"Threshold Tempo Run\",\"target_distance_km\":12,\"target_duration_minutes\":53,\"target_pace_easy_sec_per_km\":339,\"target_pace_fast_sec_per_km\":268,\"segments\":[{\"segment_type\":\"Warmup\",\"duration_minutes\":11,\"target_pace_sec_per_km\":339,\"intensity\":\"Easy\",\"repetitions\":1,\"notes\":\"2 km easy jog. Take your time here — your legs have had two days of work already this week. The warmup is doing real work: raising core temperature, increasing muscle elasticity, and preparing your cardiovascular system for threshold effort.\"},{\"segment_type\":\"Work\",\"duration_minutes\":36,\"target_pace_sec_per_km\":268,\"intensity\":\"Threshold\",\"repetitions\":1,\"notes\":\"8 km continuous at threshold pace (4:28/km). This is comfortably hard — you should be able to say a few words but not hold a conversation. Think of it as your marathon pace plus about 15 seconds per km. Steady and controlled throughout; avoid surging in the middle miles.\"},{\"segment_type\":\"Cooldown\",\"duration_minutes\":11,\"target_pace_sec_per_km\":339,\"intensity\":\"Easy\",\"repetitions\":1,\"notes\":\"2 km easy jog to bring your heart rate down gradually. Don't stop abruptly after the tempo — keep moving for the full cooldown.\"}],\"warmup_notes\":\"2 km easy jog. Optional: 2–3 strides at threshold pace in the final minute of warmup to prime your legs before the sustained effort begins.\",\"cooldown_notes\":\"2 km easy jog, then walk 3–5 minutes. Calf stretching and hip flexor work. Left Achilles check-in: any tightness or tenderness after tempo runs is worth noting and monitoring.\",\"coaching_notes\":\"Threshold running at 4:28/km is one of the most valuable sessions in your maintenance toolkit. It raises your lactate threshold — the pace you can sustain before lactate accumulates faster than you can clear it — which directly translates to marathon performance. For maintenance, 8 km of continuous tempo work is an ideal dose: enough to maintain the adaptation, not so much that it creates excessive fatigue going into your long run on Sunday. This mirrors what you've been doing successfully in recent weeks. The key execution cue: the first 2 km of the tempo should feel almost too easy. If you're working hard at 2 km, you've started too fast.\",\"perceived_effort\":7},{\"day_of_week\":5,\"workout_type\":\"Easy\",\"title\":\"Easy Aerobic Run\",\"target_distance_km\":8,\"target_duration_minutes\":45,\"target_pace_easy_sec_per_km\":339,\"target_pace_fast_sec_per_km\":322,\"segments\":[{\"segment_type\":\"Warmup\",\"duration_minutes\":5,\"target_pace_sec_per_km\":356,\"intensity\":\"Easy\",\"repetitions\":1,\"notes\":\"First 5 minutes very easy — treat it as a moving warmup.\"},{\"segment_type\":\"Work\",\"duration_minutes\":35,\"target_pace_sec_per_km\":339,\"intensity\":\"Easy\",\"repetitions\":1,\"notes\":\"Comfortable, conversational easy pace. This is a bridge run between Thursday's tempo and Sunday's long run. Keep it honest — easy means easy.\"},{\"segment_type\":\"Cooldown\",\"duration_minutes\":5,\"target_pace_sec_per_km\":356,\"intensity\":\"Easy\",\"repetitions\":1,\"notes\":\"Ease off for the final 5 minutes. Arrive home feeling fresh.\"}],\"warmup_notes\":\"Light dynamic stretching before heading out. No structured warmup needed beyond the easy opening minutes of the run.\",\"cooldown_notes\":\"Walk 2–3 minutes. Focus on calf and Achilles stretching on both sides. This is a good evening to do any foam rolling or mobility work to prepare for Sunday's long run.\",\"coaching_notes\":\"Friday's easy run serves a specific purpose: it keeps your aerobic engine running without adding fatigue before Sunday's long run. At 8 km and easy pace, the physiological cost is low but the benefit — maintaining blood flow, keeping your legs loose, and reinforcing your aerobic base — is real. Think of this as preparation for Sunday, not a standalone workout. If your legs feel unusually heavy or sore from Thursday's tempo, it's completely reasonable to shorten this to 6 km or slow the pace further. Listen to what your body is telling you.\",\"perceived_effort\":4},{\"day_of_week\":6,\"workout_type\":\"CrossTrain\",\"title\":\"Active Recovery Cross-Training\",\"target_distance_km\":0,\"target_duration_minutes\":40,\"target_pace_easy_sec_per_km\":0,\"target_pace_fast_sec_per_km\":0,\"segments\":[{\"segment_type\":\"Work\",\"duration_minutes\":40,\"target_pace_sec_per_km\":0,\"intensity\":\"Easy\",\"repetitions\":1,\"notes\":\"Choose one: easy cycling (stationary or outdoor), swimming, yoga, or light strength work (bodyweight squats, single-leg deadlifts, hip bridges, calf raises). Keep effort genuinely easy — this is active recovery, not a second workout. Heart rate should stay well below 130 bpm.\"}],\"warmup_notes\":\"5 minutes of very light movement to ease in. No need for a structured warmup given the low intensity.\",\"cooldown_notes\":\"5 minutes of gentle stretching. If doing strength work, include eccentric heel drops (3 x 15 each side) as Achilles prehab — this is a well-supported intervention for Achilles health maintenance.\",\"coaching_notes\":\"Saturday is a strategic rest-from-running day that keeps you moving without adding impact stress. With your Achilles history, managing cumulative load is important, and a non-running day before your long run is a smart structural choice. Cross-training at easy effort maintains blood flow and keeps you feeling active without compromising Sunday's long run quality. If life is busy, this can also be a full rest day — that's a legitimate choice, not a failure. The goal is to arrive at Sunday's long run feeling ready.\",\"perceived_effort\":3},{\"day_of_week\":0,\"workout_type\":\"LongRun\",\"title\":\"Aerobic Long Run\",\"target_distance_km\":20,\"target_duration_minutes\":118,\"target_pace_easy_sec_per_km\":356,\"target_pace_fast_sec_per_km\":339,\"segments\":[{\"segment_type\":\"Warmup\",\"duration_minutes\":10,\"target_pace_sec_per_km\":356,\"intensity\":\"Easy\",\"repetitions\":1,\"notes\":\"First 10 minutes at the very easy end of your range (5:56/km or slower). Your body needs time to shift into aerobic gear, especially on Sunday mornings. Resist any urge to pick up the pace early.\"},{\"segment_type\":\"Work\",\"duration_minutes\":98,\"target_pace_sec_per_km\":356,\"intensity\":\"Easy\",\"repetitions\":1,\"notes\":\"Maintain easy, aerobic effort throughout (5:22–5:56/km). The long run is not a race simulation — it's time on feet at aerobic effort. If you're running with others, you should be able to hold a full conversation. On warm days, slow down by 10–15 seconds per km and prioritize hydration. Your recent long runs (20–21 km at 5:56/km) show you're executing this well.\"},{\"segment_type\":\"Cooldown\",\"duration_minutes\":10,\"target_pace_sec_per_km\":356,\"intensity\":\"Easy\",\"repetitions\":1,\"notes\":\"Final 10 minutes, ease off slightly. Finish feeling like you worked but not depleted. Walk 5 minutes after finishing.\"}],\"warmup_notes\":\"Walk 3–5 minutes before starting. Dynamic leg swings and hip circles. No need for strides — the long run warmup is the first 10–15 minutes of easy running itself.\",\"cooldown_notes\":\"Walk 5 minutes after finishing. Prioritize: rehydration and a carbohydrate-protein snack within 30–45 minutes. Light stretching of calves, hamstrings, and hip flexors. Left Achilles check-in: note any tightness and monitor across the week.\",\"coaching_notes\":\"The Sunday long run is the cornerstone of your aerobic fitness. At 20 km, it's right in the sweet spot for a maintenance phase — long enough to sustain your aerobic adaptations (mitochondrial density, fat oxidation, cardiac stroke volume) without pushing into territory that requires extended recovery. Your recent history shows 20–21 km long runs at 5:56/km, which is exactly right. The most common long run mistake is drifting too fast in the middle miles when you're feeling good — your target is consistent easy effort from start to finish, not a negative split. Fueling note: for runs over 75 minutes, taking in some carbohydrates (a gel or similar) around the 60-minute mark supports performance and recovery. A registered dietitian can help you dial in your fueling strategy if you'd like more detail there.\",\"perceived_effort\":6}]}"
        }
      ]
    }
  ],
